---
description: Avoid em dashes in prose; use commas or shorter sentences instead
alwaysApply: true
---

# No em dash in text

Do not use the em dash character (`—`) in user-facing copy, content, docs, or comments.

Use instead:

- **Commas** for a light pause or appositive: "My first classic, a lifelong project, never really ends."
- **Shorter sentences** when the idea needs a hard break: "Nothing was perfect. Everything was earned."
- **A colon** for labels or explanations: "Expected: PASS (empty site builds to dist/)."
- **Parentheses** for brief asides: "Memory Lane (formerly owned cars)."

```markdown
<!-- BAD -->
A personal garage for the cars I love — stories, photos, and the work that never ends.

<!-- GOOD -->
A personal garage for the cars I love: stories, photos, and work that never really ends.
```

Hyphens (`-`) and en dashes in code ranges (e.g. `1970-1974`) are fine. This rule targets the em dash in prose.
